<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE DRUG CLINIC: CRACKING THE USER'S FACADE OF DENIAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOSEPH A. PURSCH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Find a need and fill it" is a wise business maxim. "Figure out what people 
need -- and they'll buy it." That sounds logical, but the nation's need for 
alcoholism treatment went unfilled -- until relatively recently. 
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s I was sitting in a think tank with alcoholism treatment 
marketers and TV advertising consultants. Research had shown there was 
definitely a need for treatment out there. The question was: How do we fill it? 
In spite of regular ads in medical journals only 5% of the patients in 
alcoholism clinics were sent by doctors. The other 95% were being brought in by 
the police, the courts or angry spouses. 
</P>
<P>
"To educate doctors doesn't pay," the admen deduced. You can always tell a 
doctor -- but not much. Did we clinicians have any better ideas? 
</P>
<P>
Well, yes. Why not take alcoholism education to the people who live with the 
problem? 
</P>
<P>
Right! The ad men positively jingled. Sutton robbed banks because that's where 
the money was, right? The disease is all over so let's take our TV ads directly 
to the living rooms of America. 
</P>
<P>
We know that the average family consists of 1.8 alcoholics/addicts and four 
co-dependents (non-alcoholics who suffer along with them). So how's this for a 
30-second ad: An introduction showing signs and symptoms, such as personality 
changes and drunk-driving arrests. These things co-dependents already know. 
Then add some things they only suspect, like memory loss and decreased life 
span. Close the piece with hope ("treatment works") and flash the clinic logo 
on the 800 number. 
</P>
<P>
Now the admen were really getting into it -- scribbling, sketching, even 
ad-libbing new terms. To rattle "heartland puritanism" and shape up "bicoastal 
sophistication," let's dramatize the ads with high-pressure soap scenes. That 
will crack what clinicians call "denial," the thing that doctors, co-dependents 
and alcoholics/addicts hide behind. 
</P>
<P>
It worked with almost Pavlovian charm. After running ads for one month, 
America's alcoholics were hauled out of closets and dragged into clinics by 
guilty co-dependents. Why? Because the ads portrayed the co-dependents as 
contributing to the demise of somebody they loved -- or hated. The clinics 
filled up and multiplied. The nation went on a treatment binge. There 
definitely was a need and the treatment "industry" had found a way to fill it. 
</P>
<P>
Not surprisingly, there were angry objections to this invasion of America's 
privacy. These ads, it was charged, were not just titillating -- they were 
actually traumatizing people's emotions; the ads were exaggerating "minor" 
family problems. 
</P>
<P>
True, the ads that got the greatest response were the ones that evoked anger, 
fear and guilt. But, the ad guys countered, do you really think that these ads 
can scare an unhappy wife so much that she will label her errant husband an 
alcoholic, drag him to a hospital, spend their hard-earned money on expensive 
treatment -- and label herself a co-dependent, to boot? No, not unless there is 
a real problem. 
</P>
<P>
Why do hospitals advertise? To fill beds. Why are the ads successful? Because 
there is a need. How do the ads achieve their goal? By breaking through the 
viewers' denial and making them aware of their need. 
</P>
<P>
Let's face it. Alcoholism and drug addiction are different from other diseases. 
If you have a headache, rash or hearing loss, you'll feel it, or you'll see it, 
or somebody will make you aware of it -- and 500,000 doctors are willing to 
treat it. 
</P>
<P>
Not so with alcoholism/addiction. That's a disease of denial: The addicts deny 
it, their families hide it, the neighbors suspect it, the bosses ignore it and 
the doctors mistreat it. 
</P>
<P>
We may not like it, but we might as well accept it. The real reason the ads 
work is because they tell troubled viewers what others (family, friends, 
bosses, doctors) should tell them, but won't. They play on anger, fear and 
guilt because that's where our soft spots are. And they invade our living rooms 
because, to paraphrase bank robber Willie Sutton, that's where the alcoholics 
are. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
