<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The largest exhibition of avant-garde art in China's history has reopened in 
Beijing, after being shut down by police when artists defied a ban on 
performance art and a sculptor shot her own work with a BB gun. The sculptor 
said she didn't regret shooting her work and that finally the piece had been 
completed. "It was something I had to do, but I didn't realize it would cause 
such a stir," said Xiao Lu, the 26-year-old artist. "The piece needed to be 
destroyed slightly to be perfected." Xiao and her boyfriend were arrested and 
spent three days in jail after the incident. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
