<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Protestant vigilantes took responsibility for killing a Roman Catholic lawyer 
in his home in Belfast, Northern Ireland. Patrick Finucane was slain Sunday by 
three men, and his wife, Geraldine, was wounded. Finucane had acted for clients 
involved in the outlawed Irish Republican Army's campaign against British rule. 
The banned Ulster Freedom Fighters claimed responsibility in a coded message 
telephoned to the British Broadcasting Corp. in Belfast. Irish nationalists 
accused a British official of making Finucane a target by saying some Northern 
Ireland lawyers were "unduly sympathetic" to guerrilla groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
